### Methods in Rust

Methods are functions defined within the context of a struct (or enum) that operate on instances of that type.

---

### Method Types

| Self Parameter | Access | Description |
|----------------|--------|-------------|
| `self` | Owned | Takes ownership of the instance |
| `&self` | Immutable borrow | Read-only access |
| `&mut self` | Mutable borrow | Can modify the instance |

---

### Defining Methods

```rust
struct Rectangle {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
}

impl Rectangle {
    // Immutable borrow
    fn area(&self) -> u32 {
        self.width * self.height
    }

    // Mutable borrow
    fn scale(&mut self, factor: u32) {
        self.width *= factor;
        self.height *= factor;
    }

    // Ownership (rare)
    fn destroy(self) {
        println!("Destroying {} x {}", self.width, self.height);
    }
}

let mut rect = Rectangle { width: 30, height: 50 };
println!("Area: {}", rect.area());
rect.scale(2);
```

> **Key Point:** Methods use `&self` by default. Use `&mut self` when you need to modify the instance. Using `self` (ownership) is rare and usually only for methods that consume the value.

codeExample:
struct Circle {
    radius: f64,
}

impl Circle {
    fn new(radius: f64) -> Circle {
        Circle { radius }
    }

    fn area(&self) -> f64 {
        std::f64::consts::PI * self.radius * self.radius
    }

    fn circumference(&self) -> f64 {
        2.0 * std::f64::consts::PI * self.radius
    }
}

fn main() {
    let circle = Circle::new(5.0);
    println!("Area: {:.2}", circle.area());
    println!("Circumference: {:.2}", circle.circumference());
}
